author: thefrenchiegardener
body: Your supermarket basil is always dying? üå±üíö I call it ¬´¬†The Basil Trauma¬†¬ª and I used this ironic naming in my last two books, to picture that these kind of ¬´¬†fails¬†¬ª can make you think that you do not have a green thumb, as you can‚Äôt keep alive a healthy thriving plant. BUT‚Ä¶This has nothing to do with you! This supermarket Basil is simply not designed to grow further, it has way too many plants for such a small pot, it is absolutely normal that it can‚Äôt grow more and enventually dies.  How to heal your Basil trauma? üå± Divide this basil into smaller groups & replant in several pots with fresh soil which will be loaded with nutrients. They will have more space to grow! üå± You can also simply cut a basil stem under a node, remove lower leaves & place in a cup of water. I change the water every day. It will develop new roots, replant it and you will have a new free plant.  How to take care of Basil? üå± Basil is a summer plant, it needs warm summer temperatures & lots of sun. Place it indoor near a sunny window. When summer temperatures are here, place your pot outdoor in a sunny spot.  I hope your basil trauma will heal very soon üôåüèº Green Love to you üíö #basil #herbs #growyourownfood #plantbased #gardeningtips #plantcare #fyfyfyfy

author: joesgarden
body: Today we are back, and I am showing you how to grow unlimited tomatoes, from just one cheap tomato plant from the store. This technique is super simple and will guarantee you the exact same variety as the mother plant. Plus it‚Äôs great if you don‚Äôt have room to start loads if seeds üòäüå± This time of the year you can buy loads of tomao plants, but you truly only need one. Anyone can use this method, as honestly its super simple to do.  Simply pot out gour tomato plant and soon it will grow. You will notice sixe shoots or suckers (as they are sometimes called) forming. These can be found between the main stem and the side branch. They need to be removed, to give your plant the best chance of a bumper harvest, but make sure you keep them.  By propagating them in fresh water you can grow roots, from these otherwise discarded plants. By then potting these cuttings in good soil, you can grow an exact clone of the mother plant. And trust me this is far quicker than starting from seed!  #tomato #plants #growyourownfood #plantbased #zerowaste #diy #garden #gardening #gardentips
stickers:
Did you know you can use just one small  Tomato plant from the store  To give you an unlimited supply of fresh tomatoes  All you need to get started is only one cheap  Tomato plant from the store  And once you get it home, grab a larger pot  Pop in a good quality soil, and plant out your tomato Soon it will grow like this  And now the magic happens  Locate a side shoot from the stem and a branch and snip them all off  Place these cuttings in fresh water  And soon roots will appear  Snip off these lower branches  And then pot them nice and deep in a good soil  Continue to grow on these cuttings  And very soon you will end up with a genetically tomato garden  Giving you a bountiful harvest, all summer long  Follow for more üå±üíöüòä

author: leafydiva
body: This Adansonii repot took me almost 2 hours! I absolutely should‚Äôve asked for help, but I thought I could handle it myself. The fact that this plant is still standing is amazing, because it got pretty banged up. It hit the ceiling fan twice and almost took out some of the plants along the wall when it fell. I had to gather up all my strength to stop it from completely falling to the floor.  I got a new planter to repot it in but after losing so many roots, I decided to keep it in the planter it was already in. We‚Äôll see if the liner I put at the bottom works. On another note, I was amazed at how good the roots looked. I actually don‚Äôt think I‚Äôve ever seen roots this healthy sitting in the water resovoir for so long. The other root bound repots I‚Äôve done had healthy roots, but there were always a few that were soft and mushy.  #Plants #planttok #plantsoftiktok #houseplants #monsteraadansonii #adansonii

stickers: Make a wildlife pond with me using an old whiskey barrel  First stop - the salon!   So muddy! Stole some gravel from my driveway to cover the base (don‚Äôt tell my boyfriend) Using rain water to fill my pond  Time to add some rocks and plants to attract wildlife  I chose this Fibre Optic plant with tiny white flowers a Chinese Marsh Flower a Marsh Marigold which will spread on the surface and create shade for frogs and Water Iris which is perfect for dragonflies  I used aquatic soil to give my new plants the best start  Nice and cosy  Adding gravel stops the soil from escaping and keeps plants secure  This is Hornwort and will help to oxygenate the water. It‚Äôs so easy to plant  - just pop it in!  I made a little staircase out of rocks so the critters can climb in and out of the pond  Yay - my first resident just arrived The water will clear in a day or two as everything settles I love my new pond. I hope the animals will like it too.

author: greenhousecabinetz
body: Planting a mango seedü•≠ #mangoseed #mangotrees #plantsarefriendstoo #planthacks
stickers:
Potte mango plante i jord One month ago I took a mango seed, peeled it and wrapped it in a damped paper towel  I placed it in a ziplock bag and had it in my pantry for 10 days 10 days later it looked like this It had developed a root, so I placed the seed on a small bottle making sure the root was* covered with water I changed water weekly, 3 weeks later it look like this It has grown so fast! So I found a small plastic pot with drainage holes and filled it with soil  Placed the mango seed in the pot And filled the pot up with soil making sure the roots were covered  I use a soilmix out of soil, perlite and orchid bark I usually use 1/3 of each element  I do this to give the plant a more chunky soilmix and to prevent root rot And this is how it turned out I gave it a good rinse of water and I will continue to keep the soil moist  for the next couple of weeks  That was it I placed it back in my greenhouse cabinet to give it optimal conditions considering light, humidity and temperature

You‚Äôre supposed to use them as you would any potted plant and only water when the plant needs watered. Then, you dump water in the reservoir and it sucks it up from the bottom. Self watering pots are just fancier, more expensive cache pots. author: thefrenchiegardener
body: A perfect tree for small gardens or balconies : Kumquat üçäüíö The taste of kumquat is simply divine! You can eat the fruit with the peel and it will make a wonderful sweet tart balanced flavor. Honestly, I could eat it every morning and what a pleasure to harvest it fresh from the balcony!  Gardening tips for a kumquat tree :  üçä Place in a pot of 20L / 5 Gallon or bigger üçä Add some fresh and rich soil with compost üçä Add mulch on top for better water retention üçä Place it in full sun üçä Once repotted, fertilize 6 weeks after with Guano manure which will enhance fructification üçä Keep the soil slightly moist but not soaked. Overwatering can harm the plant üçä Kumquat can resist light frost, protect with wintering veil in winter or host it indoor On top of Kumquat tree, I would also highly recommend Lemon trees or Calamondin trees for small space gardening. And if you want other ideas, have a look at dwarf trees. There are many fascinating varieties for containers! Green Love to you üíö #kumquat  #fruit  #tree  #gardening #plantbased  #smallspacegardening  #growyourownfood #foryoupage

When I buy healthy plants, I don‚Äôt typically repot right away but when it‚Äôs a rescue I bring it him, let it acclimate for a few days, and then get in those roots to see what‚Äôs going on. Soft, mushy, and smelly roots tells you there‚Äôs root rot. Dry and brittle, tells you that it‚Äôs been underwatered.  If you are JUST starting with plants, I would purchase plants that are overall healthy and gradually move to rescue plants.
